text.b: SUMMARY OF LEFT TURN LANE FEASIBILITY STUDY

page.text: Hillsborough County’s Public Works Department – Traffic Engineering Section
requested a “Traffic Data Collection & Studies Report” for Bell Shoals Road and
Waterford Run Drive in Hillsborough County, Florida. This study was performed to
collect traffic characteristics and perform an eastbound to northbound left turn
feasibility study at the entrance of Waterford on the Alafia. Bayside Engineering, Inc.
did not have a conflict of interest with a private sector (non-governmental) client related
The entrance is located within the Bloomingdale area of the county. It is approximately
580 feet north of Boyette Road/FishHawk Boulevard. Waterford Run Drive provides
an entrance into the gated community of Waterford on the Alafia. The area is
suburban in nature. A project location map is provided as an attachment.
Existing conditions were summarized from data collected in the field, aerial images and
a review of existing documents. The functional classification was identified in the Level
of Service (LOS) Report dated March 2011, prepared by the Hillsborough County
Development Services Department. Improvements to Bell Shoals Road are currently
under construction from Boyette Road to north of Waterford Run Drive. These
improvements are adding a second thru lane in each direction, a median with a left
turn lane and directional opening for northbound Bell Shoals Road traffic turning onto
Waterford Run Drive, and an exclusive right turn lane from southbound Bell Shoals
Road onto Waterford Run Drive. Improvements on Bell Shoals Road at Boyette
Road/FishHawk Boulevard include exclusive left and right turn lanes. A layout of these
improvements is included in the Attachments. The following is a summary of the

Waterford Run Drive is stop controlled approaching Bell Shoals Road. The LOS
Report identified Bell Shoals Road from Bloomingdale Road to Boyette Road as
having LOS F during the peak hour.
There are several schools within two miles of this location including Cimino Elementary
School, Burns Middle School, Valrico Academy, and Bloomingdale High School.
Burns Middle and Bloomingdale have bus stops at this location. Cimino Elementary
drops off and picks up students at a nearby location within the gated community.
Currently, there are roadway improvements being constructed on Bell Shoals Road.
The two-lane undivided section is being reconstructed to four lanes divided. A
directional median is currently being proposed at this location. The median would
allow a northbound left turn onto Waterford Run Drive.
The traffic data collection and studies were performed following the procedures in the
Florida Department of Transportation (FDOT) Manual of Uniform Traffic Studies
(MUTS) and the Federal Highway Administration (FHWA) Manual on Uniform Traffic
Manual vehicle turning movement counts were collected at the intersection for
an eight-hour period on Tuesday, March 5, 2013. The turning movement counts
were collected during the following hours:
The intersection AM peak occurred between 7:00 a.m. and 8:00 a.m. primarily
from drivers commuting to work. The intersection mid-day off-peak occurred
between 12:00 a.m. and 1:00 p.m. The intersection PM peak occurred between
4:45 p.m. and 5:45 p.m. primarily from drivers commuting home from work. No
pedestrians or bicyclist were observed during the eight hours of the study. The
peak hour left turn volume on Waterford Run Drive was 22 vehicles, with one

over that period, with one (1) crash occurring in
2008, two (2) crashes in 2009, and one (1) crash each for 2010, 2011, and
2012. Of the six crashes over the five-year period, three (3) were rear-end
crashes, and three (3) were lane departures crashes. Two (2) accidents
resulted in injuries. Of the six crashes, three (3) occurred during night time and
three (3) occurred during daylight hours. No crashes occurred during the am
study period; one (1) of the crashes occurred during the mid-day study period;
and one (1) crash occurred during the pm study period.
The crash history at this intersection suggests a pattern of northbound rear-end
crashes. This may be due to vehicles stopping to turn left onto Waterford Run
Drive. However, no more than two (2) correctable crashes occurred during any
A field review was conducted of the intersection operation to identify
characteristics relevant to the evaluation of a left turn movement for the
intersection. A summary of the operational characteristics is provided below.

The southbound traffic on Bell Shoals Road had a rolling queue during
the AM and PM peak approaching Boyette/FishHawk Road. The queue
was significant and extended past the Waterford entrance.

Eastbound to northbound left turns had minimal delay. The queue on

There are spacing criteria for median openings according to Section 6.04 of the
Hillsborough County Land Development Code to adequately meet operational
and safety requirements. Bell Shoals Road is considered an Access Class 6
roadway due to the adjacent land being moderately developed and subdivided.
It is distinguished by existing non-restrictive median treatments. After
completion of the current construction and the addition of a restrictive median,
this section of Bell Shoals Road will be considered an Access Class 5.
According to Section 6.04.07, the minimum spacing requirement for a Class 5
roadway is 660 feet between full and directional openings. This spacing may be
increased, based on traffic engineering principles, if the safety or operation of
the intersection will be affected. Table 1 below shows the Minimum Spacing
Table found in the Land Development Code.

The minimum width for a median to allow a passenger vehicle a two-step
crossing maneuver is 25 feet. The proposed median will be 22’ wide; therefore
the vehicle must be able to make a left turn out of Waterford Run Drive in one
step. The required intersection sight distance for 45 mph is 590 feet for a
passenger vehicle, 810 feet for a single unit truck, and 930 feet for a WB-40 or
WB-50 semi-trailer per FDOT Standard Index 546 (see Attachment).
There is an opening in the median on Waterford Run Drive with a 6-foot
crosswalk 11 feet from the edge of the Bell Shoals Road pavement. This
places the stop bar approximately 21 feet from the edge of pavement. From
field observations and measurements, the sight distance at this location is
approximately 700 feet to the north. This meets the criteria for a passenger
vehicle but not for any heavy vehicle that may need to perform this maneuver.

The traffic data collection and study was performed following the procedures in the
FDOT MUTS and FHWA MUTCD. The purpose of the evaluation and conclusion of
the study is to provide input into the decision of whether conditions at Bell Shoals Road
and Waterford Run Drive warrant the installation of a median opening for an
There is no history of significant crashes at this location with the current roadway
geometry. Due to the not-yet-complete widening and addition of the median, the
ultimate operational characteristics are still unknown. However, traffic engineering
principles need to be applied in order to ensure a safe and effective roadway for all
users. This includes reducing the probability and severity of crashes.
This location does not meet the minimum median opening requirement, and the
location of the opening encroaches on the functional boundary of the intersection. The
current construction will add left and right turn lanes at the nearby signal at Boyette
Road and widen the roadway to include two lanes of through traffic. Most southbound
vehicles will make lane-changing decisions as they approach Waterford Run Drive in
order to prepare themselves for their movement at the signalized intersection. Having
vehicles crossing two lanes of traffic at this location will overload the southbound driver
who is currently engaged in his movement for the upcoming signal and may not see
the crossing vehicle from Waterford Run Drive.
Bell Shoals Road at Waterford Run Drive
Due to the long queues on the southbound approach, sight distance is decreased.
While there are ‘Samaritan’ vehicles that allow left turn traffic to pass, visibility for the
through northbound traffic is significantly reduced, increasing the probability of a crash.
This section of roadway does not provide the recommended distance for vehicles on
Waterford Run Drive, to make a right turn onto Bell Shoals Road, merge to the left turn
lane and make a U-turn at Boyette Road. However, this maneuver allows for proper
sight distance and allows the driver to make a more accurate judgment of the gap
available. This makes a right turn safer to execute than a left turn. The 22’ median
that will be provided at Boyette Road will allow proper width for a U-turn maneuver at
The field reviews, conclusions, and recommendations were conducted by a
professional traffic operations engineer licensed by the Florida Board of Professional
The recommendation of this study is to not include an eastbound to northbound left
turn movement and maintain the current design of the directional median on Bell
Shoals Road at Waterford Run Drive.
